Reasoning: 

1. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) - The paper discusses the structure of software networks and their differences from other types of networks such as social networks. The concept of node mixing and group structure is also relevant to social networks. 

2. cs.SE (Software Engineering) - The paper discusses the practical applications of the observed group structure in software engineering. 

3. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) - The paper compares the node mixing in software networks with that in the Internet and discusses the differences. 

4. cs.CY (Computers and Society) - The paper discusses the implications of the observed group structure in software networks on society and software development. 

5. cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) - Although not the main focus of the paper, the concept of node mixing and group structure is relevant to cryptography and security in networked systems.
